<div class='toload example'>
<p><span class='envidentifier'>Example 1.3.13</span>
Given an infinite set $P$ of integers, we consider the topology on $\mathbb{Z}$ generated by the sets $p\mathbb{Z}+a$, where $a\in\mathbb{Z}$ and $p\in P$. This makes $\mathbb{Z}$ a non-discrete (i.e., non-Ã©tale), countable, second-countable, zero-dimensional, non-locally compact, Hausdorff topological group.
</p>
